{
  "_what": "Analysis + methodology for the 'Speaker's Initiative to Address Citywide Needs' Schedule C category, used to split its dollars across the app's 5 nonprofit sectors in HISTORICAL_TREND_DATA.",
  "_problem": "In the Schedule C reconciliation summary, 'Speaker's Initiative to Address Citywide Needs' is a single catch-all line with no service description. In FY27 it is $86,522,049 = 13.2% of the entire discretionary budget and was previously dumped 100% into the 'Social Services' sector, which overstated that sector (it read 60.4% of FY27).",
  "_source": "BetaNYC/New-York-City-Budget  data/combined/all_years_awards.csv (award-level; columns include year, category, initiative, award_type, member, organization, program, ein, amount, agency, purpose).",
  "_finding": "The 'initiative' column just repeats the category name for this catch-all, but every underlying award IS tagged with an administering city agency (agency column). The agency reveals the true service: e.g. FY27's $86.4M of Speaker awards is 42.1% DYCD (youth), 15.9% DCLA (arts/culture), 7.2% DHMH + 5.4% DFTA (health/aging), 6.1% DCWP (a single $5.3M 'Save for College' financial-empowerment program), etc.",
  "_method": "For each fiscal year with award-level data (FY2020-FY2027), the reconciliation Speaker dollar amount is split across the 5 sectors in proportion to that year's Speaker awards grouped by administering agency (agencyToSector map below). Distributing the RECONCILIATION amount (not the awards-CSV amount) keeps every year's sector sums reconciling exactly to the real Grand Total, even though the awards-CSV Speaker total and the reconciliation Speaker total diverge in some years (the two BetaNYC products categorize differently). For FY2016-FY2019 no award-level Speaker data exists, so those dollars remain in socialServices and are explicitly NOT deciphered.",
  "_caveats": [
    "agencyToSector is an approximation. DYCD ('Youth AND Community Development') is mapped wholesale to youthEducation though a minority of its awards fund community development; this is the single largest assumption (DYCD is ~42% of the FY27 Speaker pool).",
    "FY2017 ($30.1M) and FY2018 ($20.5M) carry material undeciphered Speaker amounts still sitting in socialServices, inflating those two years' social share relative to FY2020+ where the same category is deciphered. This is a data-availability seam, not a real trend break.",
    "Only the 'Speaker's Initiative' category is agency-redistributed. All other categories have informative names and are mapped by name in sector-category-mapping.json."
  ],
